Oh I think you=E2=80=99re going to=C2=A0see more of this:BTCS Inc. (Nasdaq:=
 BTCS) (=E2=80=9CBTCS=E2=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D), a blockch=
ain technology-focused company, has announced the first-ever dividend payab=
le in Bitcoin by a Nasdaq-listed company, which the Company refers to as a =
Bividend. ...=E2=80=9CWe want to reward our long-time shareholders for thei=
r continued support and encourage financial freedom by providing the means =
to enable direct ownership of Bitcoin and other digital assets,=E2=80=9D st=
ated Charles Allen, Chief Executive Officer of BTCS. =E2=80=A6Allen continu=
ed, =E2=80=9CNow, we are the first Nasdaq-listed company to pay a Bividend,=
 a dividend payable in Bitcoin at the option of our shareholders. This is a=
 moment we have long anticipated since the Company purchased the domain, bi=
vidend.com, in February 2015. BTCS is now in the financial position require=
d to execute on the Company=E2=80=99s vision.=E2=80=9D With BTCS=E2=80=99 y=
ear-end 2021 stock price of $3.14 per share representing a 12.6% discount t=
o the Company=E2=80=99s digital asset holdings and cash position of $3.56 p=
er share, or $37.8 million, this is an ideal time to reward our shareholder=
s with a non-taxable return-of-capital Bividend.Sure. BTCS is a somewhat=C2=
=A0unloved micro-cap company; yesterday it closed at $3.03 per share for a =
market cap of about $31 million, on volume of about 94,000 shares. As of 11=
 a.m. today it had traded 18.9 million shares and was up 52% to $4.61. I ha=
ve often  argued in this column that if you are a small public company you =
should talk a lot about crypto and memes and stuff to increase shareholder =
value. BTCS is a crypto company anyway, but you can always talk=C2=A0more=
=C2=A0about crypto. A bividend is a terrible name but an obviously good mem=
e-y crypto stunt to increase attention. BTCS will pay about $500,000 in biv=
idends, which bought it about $15 million of market cap. Just a good trade!=
More interesting than the announcement, though, is the little form you have=
 to fill out to get your bividend. (It=E2=80=99s also filed with the SEC.) =
I think you=E2=80=99re supposed to do it online (there=E2=80=99s that websi=
te), but if I were a BTCS shareholder I=E2=80=99d be tempted to print a cop=
y, fill it out in pen, mail it to BTCS=E2=80=99s main address=C2=A0and see =
what they do. (I bet it=E2=80=99d work! Boy is that not investing advice!)=
=C2=A0You write down your name, Social Security number, phone number=C2=A0a=
nd email, and then you write down your Bitcoin wallet address, and then you=
 write the Bitcoin wallet address again to confirm that it=E2=80=99s right.=
 (=E2=80=9CBitcoin transactions are irreversible it is advised that you cut=
 and paste your wallet address into this field,=E2=80=9D says the form, sug=
gesting that pen-and-paper is not the preferred method, though I suppose yo=
u could print your Bitcoin wallet address and then use literal scissors and=
 paste.)My broader point here is that the system of stock ownership runs on=
 different rails from the system of crypto ownership. For instance, it is p=
retty unusual, in the U.S., to actually own stock in your own name. Most st=
ock is owned in the name of a thing called =E2=80=9CCede & Co.,=E2=80=9D a =
=E2=80=9Cnominee=E2=80=9D for the Depository Trust Co., the big U.S. stock =
clearinghouse. And then DTC keeps a list of the brokers who =E2=80=9Creally=
=E2=80=9D own its shares, and those brokers keep their own lists of the cus=
tomers who =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D own their shares. So if you buy a share=
 of stock through your broker, what you own is a notation in the broker=E2=
=80=99s database saying that you are entitled to one share, and what the br=
oker owns is a notation in DTC=E2=80=99s database saying that it is entitle=
d to one share. DTC/Cede, meanwhile, actually owns the share, which is to s=
ay that Cede owns a notation in the issuer=E2=80=99s transfer agent=E2=80=
=99s database saying that it is entitled to one share. Actual share ownersh=
ip =E2=80=94=C2=A0=E2=80=9Crecord=E2=80=9D ownership =E2=80=94=C2=A0means b=
eing on the transfer agent=E2=80=99s list.=C2=A0This can seem like a ricket=
y system, though it mostly works pretty well. (There  are some  gaps!) In t=
he long run it is an obvious improvement over the prior system of, like, ev=
eryone owned paper stock certificates and had to cart them around to settle=
 trades and if you lost your certificate you were out of luck. But the DTC =
system is decades old at this point and it is not hard to imagine a simpler=
 system. Sometimes the people who go around imagining simpler systems imagi=
ne=C2=A0blockchain-based systems. =E2=80=9CWe=E2=80=99ll have one ledger of=
 share ownership, and [the big banks and brokers][DTC][an open system of=C2=
=A0crypto miners] will maintain that ledger reliably,=E2=80=9D is the think=
ing there.But here we are in the actual world of 2022, where most people ow=
n stock through their brokers. This creates problems for bividends. When a =
company pays a cash dividend, it pretty much wires the money to DTC, which =
wires the money to brokerage firms, which deposit the money in their custom=
ers=E2=80=99=C2=A0accounts. But owning crypto is still sort of fraught for =
brokerages and DTC: There are regulatory=C2=A0custody obligations=C2=A0and=
=C2=A0capital requirements for holding crypto yourself, and you can=E2=80=
=99t deposit crypto in a customer account unless you=C2=A0let your customer=
s hold crypto in their accounts, which is sort of a momentous decision for =
an old-school=C2=A0retail brokerage.=C2=A0So if a company said =E2=80=9Cwe=
=E2=80=99re going to pay a dividend in Bitcoin=E2=80=9D it =E2=80=A6=C2=A0k=
ind of =E2=80=A6=C2=A0wouldn=E2=80=99t =E2=80=A6=C2=A0work? Like, it would =
have to send the Bitcoins to DTC=E2=80=99s Bitcoin wallet, and DTC would ha=
ve to send them to the brokerages=E2=80=99 wallets, and some of them would =
not have wallets and=C2=A0would get pretty upset. For that matter a lot of=
=C2=A0investors=C2=A0would get pretty upset: If you run a stock mutual fund=
, you might invest in the stock of BTCS, but your mandate might not allow B=
itcoin investing, you might not have a Bitcoin wallet, and you might have t=
rouble complying with your own custody obligations.[1] So a Bitcoin dividen=
d would cause a lot of havoc for the intermediaries in the financial system=
.This is sort of a known thing, to the point that a=C2=A0selling point=C2=
=A0of crypto dividends is sometimes =E2=80=9Clet=E2=80=99s cause havoc for =
the financial system by doing a crypto dividend.=E2=80=9D Overstock.com Inc=
.  tried it in 2019 to hassle short sellers, and last month  I half-jokingl=
