</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Oh I think you=E2=80=99re going to=C2=
=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26265348.275651=
/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MzYyMjkvMDAwMTQ5Mz=
E1MjIyMDAwMzk2L2V4OTktMS5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB04880fe5" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
see more of this</a>:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">BTCS Inc.=
 (Nasdaq: BTCS) (=E2=80=9CBTCS=E2=80=9D or the =E2=80=9CCompany=E2=80=9D), =
a blockchain technology-focused company, has announced the first-ever divid=
end payable in Bitcoin by a Nasdaq-listed company, which the Company refers=
 to as a Bividend. ...</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CWe want to =
reward our long-time shareholders for their continued support and encourage=
 financial freedom by providing the means to enable direct ownership of Bit=
coin and other digital assets,=E2=80=9D stated Charles Allen, Chief Executi=
ve Officer of BTCS. =E2=80=A6</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Allen continu=
ed, =E2=80=9CNow, we are the first Nasdaq-listed company to pay a Bividend,=
 a dividend payable in Bitcoin at the option of our shareholders. This is a=
 moment we have long anticipated since the Company purchased the domain, bi=
vidend.com, in February 2015. BTCS is now in the financial position require=
d to execute on the Company=E2=80=99s vision.=E2=80=9D With BTCS=E2=80=99 y=
ear-end 2021 stock price of $3.14 per share representing a 12.6% discount t=
o the Company=E2=80=99s digital asset holdings and cash position of $3.56 p=
er share, or $37.8 million, this is an ideal time to reward our shareholder=
s with a non-taxable return-of-capital Bividend.</p></blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure. BTCS is a somewhat=C2=A0unloved micro-cap compan=
y; yesterday it closed at $3.03 per share for a market cap of about $31 mil=
lion, on volume of about 94,000 shares. As of 11 a.m. today it had traded 1=
8.9 million shares and was up 52% to $4.61. I have often <a href=3D"https:/=
/link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26265348.275651/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxv=
b21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMTEtMDQvbWFjeS1zLXRhcmdldGVkLWJ=
5LW1lbWUtYWN0aXZpc3RzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDUyMl9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW=
1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZXJtPTIyMDEwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249b=
W9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf832d2f8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" ite=
mscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decora=
tion: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0000=
00; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> argued</a> in thi=
s column that if you are a small public company you should talk a lot about=
 crypto and memes and stuff to increase shareholder value. BTCS is a crypto=
 company anyway, but you can always talk=C2=A0<em>more=C2=A0</em>about cryp=
to. A bividend is a terrible name but an obviously good meme-y crypto stunt=
 to increase attention. BTCS will pay about $500,000 in bividends, which bo=
ught it about $15 million of market cap. Just a good trade!</p><p style=3D"=
margin: 16px 0;">More interesting than the announcement, though, is <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26265348.275651/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE0MzYyMjkvMDAwMTQ5MzE1MjIyMDAw=
Mzk2L2V4OTktMy5odG0/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB606367b4" itemprop=3D"StoryLin=
k" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-=
decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color:=
 #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">the little f=
orm</a> you have to fill out to get your bividend. (It=E2=80=99s also filed=
 with the SEC.) I think you=E2=80=99re supposed to do it online (there=E2=
=80=99s that website), but if I were a BTCS shareholder I=E2=80=99d be temp=
ted to print a copy, fill it out in pen, mail it to BTCS=E2=80=99s main add=
ress=C2=A0and see what they do. (I bet it=E2=80=99d work! Boy is that not i=
nvesting advice!)=C2=A0You write down your name, Social Security number, ph=
one number=C2=A0and email, and then you write down your Bitcoin wallet addr=
ess, and then you write the Bitcoin wallet address again to confirm that it=
=E2=80=99s right. (=E2=80=9CBitcoin transactions are irreversible it is adv=
ised that you cut and paste your wallet address into this field,=E2=80=9D s=
ays the form, suggesting that pen-and-paper is not the preferred method, th=
ough I suppose you could print your Bitcoin wallet address and then use lit=
eral scissors and paste.)</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">My broader point =
here is that the system of stock ownership runs on different rails from the=
 system of crypto ownership. For instance, it is pretty unusual, in the U.S=
., to actually own stock in your own name. Most stock is owned in the name =
of a thing called =E2=80=9CCede &amp; Co.,=E2=80=9D a =E2=80=9Cnominee=E2=
=80=9D for the Depository Trust Co., the big U.S. stock clearinghouse. And =
then DTC keeps a list of the brokers who =E2=80=9Creally=E2=80=9D own its s=
hares, and those brokers keep their own lists of the customers who =E2=80=
=9Creally=E2=80=9D own their shares. So if you buy a share of stock through=
 your broker, what you own is a notation in the broker=E2=80=99s database s=
aying that you are entitled to one share, and what the broker owns is a not=
ation in DTC=E2=80=99s database saying that it is entitled to one share. DT=
C/Cede, meanwhile, actually owns the share, which is to say that Cede owns =
a notation in the issuer=E2=80=99s transfer agent=E2=80=99s database saying=
 that it is entitled to one share. Actual share ownership =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Crecord=E2=80=9D ownership =E2=80=94=C2=A0means being on the transf=
er agent=E2=80=99s list.=C2=A0</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This can see=
m like a rickety system, though it mostly works pretty well. (There <a href=
=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/26265348.275651/aHR0cHM6L=
y93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMTUtMDctMTQvYmFua3MtZm9y=
Z290LXdoby13YXMtc3VwcG9zZWQtdG8tb3duLWRlbGwtc2hhcmVzP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAxMDUyMl9=
NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZX=
JtPTIyMDEwNSZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB090f2=
c1f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> are</a> some <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.c=
om/click/26265348.275651/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydG=
